@Horatius Kyodu Horatius Kyodu

Horatius raises an eyebrow, but eventually shrugs. "…They were nice enough. To be honest, I don't remember much about them. Maybe that's because I was only 10 years old when they…" After a short pause, they continue. "But at the same time, you don't really understand how important something is until you learn to stop taking it for granted. Nothing's really felt 'normal' since then, y'know?"

"Yeah. I wonder about that. What 'normal' people are like. It's almost hard for me to think about. Like, what do you even spend your time doing? I guess when you reach a certain age you pick some trade or career...I suppose I wasn't forced to deviate too much from that." 
Wress scratches his head. "I just feel like I'm not feeling right. Like this is an event I should be happy about. But I wish this never came up. Not now. You don't mix up personal and professional life."

They laugh a little at this. "Yeah, I get the feeling. Even if my parents came back now somehow, I don't know if I'd even be able to come back to *them*. Not as whoever 'Horatius Kyodu' is supposed to be. I'm sure I'd never hear the end of the shit Phin would give me for it." There's another brief pause in their speech, this time accompanied by their expression growing a little more uncomfortable. "…My asshole brother, I mean. If *he* were here, I'd…"

They clear their throat. "I think what's important is that you don't hate her, right? Maybe there's a lot you two have to work out, and when you really feel like it, you can try. But you don't have to force yourself to reconcile everything right now. If you want to focus on professional life, let her be a professional associate. Nothing's going to get in the way of that until you're ready."

"Mgh. Maybe that's true. It's not like she's been trying to get overly sentimental or initiate anything. I might be making a big fuss out of noth--"

Two people step into the carriage. One is Thelma. The other is a woman holding her at gunpoint, recognizable from the earlier shitshow with Erica. The maid. "I am going to travel with your caravan. Are there any objections?"

"What the fuck?!" Wress yells out, standing up immediately and readying himself for some kind of encounter.
Horatius also stands up, their body tense but not yet in a fighting stance. "May I ask why?"

"I hold no stake in the goals of your group. I simply need to arrive at the capital as quickly as possible without exhausting all energy by travelling on foot." She explains the very obvious fact that she means no harm, which was very clear by her behavior.
"You could've just… asked?" They stare at her in disbelief.
"I just did."

She does the revolver ocelot thing, removing the weapon at least from being directly pointed at Thelma. Thelma breathes a sigh of relief.
"Are you insinuating you would have done so as an act of *charity*? Do not mock me."

"Well, this one's got communication skills aplenty…" they mutter to themself. "You're here now, anyway. If you want a ride to the capital, you can sit down and stop waving that gun around."
They turn to Wress, whispering: "You said this chick is delusional, right? She's not going to try to kill all of us if we let her come?"

She sits down. Thelma hesitantly gives a signal for the caravan to continue forwards.

Wress responds. "I don't know anything about this lady. The one she was with -- the person who tried to pretend to be you -- *that's* the delusional one. But given what just happened, my hopes aren't high."
"I guess it wouldn't be like my life to not make me deal with a new lunatic every other day." They sigh and sit down as well.
"You're wrong." The maid says this after a brief gap in conversation. "About her. She isn't 'delusional'." Her ears are, apparently, better than assumed.

"Oh, really?" they respond, trying to hide a smirk. If anything, they should just let this slide, but they can't deny their curiousness about this doppelgänger, and right now could be an excellent chance to learn more. "How do you figure that?"
"To be delusional implies a disparity between the fundamental assumptions one holds and reality. Erica Furuda does not and has never had anything of the sort."
"Mm." Maybe it was a better idea not to ask. "So is she the real Horatius Kyodu too, then? What does that make me?"
"No, I think she's cast aside the aesthetic downgrade by now. But for a brief moment, certainly. There was no realer Horatius Kyodu."
"Well, she certainly sounds like an important person then. Can I assume you have proof of these things?"

"Where I am from, there is a logical conundrum known as a 'Devil's Proof.' Proving the presence of some more abstract 'Horatiusness' is impossible. The onus is on you to find a reason it can't be there."

*Well, I tried.* "Not much room for argument there." Horatius shrugs in resignation. "I don't have any real reason to debate this with you, if that's what you want to believe. As long as they're not in my way, it's not like I care who is or isn't Horatius."

"That is a wise outlook to have." She turns to look directly at Horatius. "Of course, this is not to say that I have any extended interest in denying your identity. Erica has abandoned such a farce, and I have no desire to cultivate hostility without cause." She bows. "My name is Rene. Until the moment I am reunited with my liege, if you have anything you want from me, please let me know."

"...Thanks. It's, uh, nice to meet you?" It's a little unnerving how almost pleasant this interaction is. They should probably ask for something, but what could they... Oh, right.
"Actually, I was wondering... Erica, like me, recently became involved with this thing called 'The Antarctica Project'; I imagine you know about that. I've been trying to figure out what's going on behind it, to unravel why it's been happening to me, and her, and the rest of our seemingly random group of people. Is there anything you know about it that you could tell me?"

"The Antarctica Project is spearheaded by men in both of the two locations it affects. The participants on Earth were selected according to an objective metric of power. I do not know why the other half of participants was selected. The operation on Earth is headed most centrally by Erica's father, Zaquera Culbasko. I, again, cannot say who is in charge here. I would likely be able to find that out, though."

Wress, who is still here, speaks up. "That... would be helpful. This whole business has been nothing but a long series of inconveniences to us, and someone actually here would be, more, ah, possible to deal with..."

Rene barely acknowledges him. "The primary goal of the Antarctica Project is to allow Erica Furuda to determine which of these two worlds should be allowed to continue existing."

Horatius starts sweating. They're reasonably sure that Rene is just exaggerating in her devotion to Erica, but...
"...Putting aside the matter of why, i-if that's true, what would happen to the people of the world she decided against existing?"
For some reason, their thoughts flash back to something Voreverl of all people said to them. *"Now that I know it's all fake, I can't say I care. It's not really evil to conquer a fake world."*
She'd just been delusional back then too, right? At least... that's what they'd assumed. But if things kept lining up this way...
"Have you ever had a dream, Horatius? Not in the abstract, flowery sense of a wish or future ambition. I mean the state human beings enter during sleep."
"Uh. Yeah...?"

"What happens to the dream when you wake up?"

The carriage stops. Thelma, exiting the realm of NPC with nothing to contribute to the conversation and entering the realm of not even being in the space of the conversation, grumbles "what now" and peeks out.

"Th... You're saying....." They don't even process the carriage stopping or Thelma's dialogue as they sit thinking about this concept, their head spinning. *All of this time... All this effort spent trying to fight, trying to change things... Is it really going to all be for nothing...? All just a dream, because some girl I don't know decided my world has less of a right to exist than another one?*
*Should I kill her? No, she's clearly too important to a lot of people with a lot of power. It would be suicide to directly oppose her if what Rene's saying is true.*
*So... What? Should I beg for my own existence? Can I even convince her to spare my world, when she's not from it in the first place? Why would they put someone like that in charge of a decision like this?! I have to find some way to prevent this from happening. Maybe if I can find some way to meet up with her or communicate with her, I can get more information on what's going on. It's worth more of a shot than just waiting to be erased, at the very least.*
*Didn't... Didn't that PDA device have a channel with questions relating to this? Maybe I can confirm whether Rene's telling the truth here, or if she's just full of shit...*
Horatius tries to pull out their PDA.
Horatius does have their PDA.
"I don't care if I look like a moron... Tell me I'm wrong about this..." Horatius mutters this as they type their responses into the #thought-provoking channel.
HK: One of the most central figures responsible for The Antarctica Project is a man from Earth named Zaquera Culbasko.
HK: The goal of The Antarctica Project is primarily to allow Erica Furuda to determine whether Earth or Arctica is a world more deserving of continued existence.
PH: The first is correct.
PH: I don't think I understand the other response fully. But it's definitely not a cohesive or reasonable answer.
HK: Thanks.
Wress leaves the carriage.

For the first time since hearing Rene speak, Horatius breathes a sigh of relief at the response their PDA gave, and looks up to see Wress leaving. "Uh- Wait, where are you going?" They follow after him.

There is a man who has stopped the carriage. His eyes light up when he sees Wress. “You!”

“I was handling it, you idiot! You’re a wanted man!” Thelma screams at him.

Two men stand opposed. Despite the proximity to a large center of population, no one is around aside from these two and two others. The larger remainder of the party associated with the younger man is lagging behind. They will not arrive until this has already concluded.

The two others include one of the heroes proper of this “story”, as well as a woman who plays more of a supporting role. They will, however, not be playing a role in this confrontation, in accordance with the wishes of all parties involved.

It is not cowardice, or any sort of inherently gendered behavior, that drives this retreat; rather it is because of practicality and respect. Only those who reside in the same world have the right to judge them for fleeing. But regardless. They will not understand the nuance reserved for those within the compressed time of initiative. No one but the two combatants, and all of us here.

This appears a stalemate for quite some time. The white knight remains motionless. He is affiliated with “order”. He makes his terms clear. They must surrender, they have the right to something something, you understand the gist.
The black knight, who subverts order, is going to move first. Sorry for the spoilers, but that should be obvious.

The white knight knows that, if his terms were accepted, the black knight would be subject to a short trial, followed by death. He knows that the black knight is likely aware of this, and therefore would never willingly surrender. Though even without this lethality, the ideologue was not likely to give into coercion. That’s just the kind of guy he is, apparently.

The black knight knows the white knight knows this, that it is an open secret that the proper resolution to an arrest was never on the table. The agent of chaos seeks only to disrupt the system. To surrender would already be death. The black knight knows the white knight is only bothering out of obligation to his role. For honor, for his worthless male pride.
Interactions become a lot more dull when everyone knows everything. Gone are schemes, gone are ideologies. Now it’s just about the black knight preparing himself and searching for an opportunity.

He finds whatever he thought he was looking for, and the progression of time resumes. He feigns left, but stabs right, barely missing the jugular as the sharp instrument finds its home somewhere closer to the back of the neck. The pain doesn’t phase his opponent, though. The white knight is fueled by endless adrenaline, a veritable beast of a man.

His presence here at all is a fluke, one of either fortune or misfortune for the rebellion. He longed for his younger years. For real field work, when men were men, and he wasn’t forced into an office (he willingly transferred to), dealing with an abstract fight. So he wandered off. He’s essentially a vigilante, but his word is certainly law here. There are always those who surpass the law.

“You’re a lot shorter than I expected.” He says. One wonders how long he’s been waiting for an opportunity for that one-liner. The white knight lives for the crowd, but is somehow incredibly ineffective at drawing it. From birth, his ‘wyrd’ guaranteed him a status of second banana at most. He has no war to fight, and until very recently, no uprising to crush. His only avenue for direct combat would’ve been pest control, which he found to be below his ego.

The black knight is his diametric opposite. In the absence of interfering factors, one can easily imagine him turning out a mild mannered boy working some mundane office job. But the world had other plans, and he idolized a lifestyle he hated, as everyone he knew molded him by their expectations. The leader of those who seek freedom would likely be happier as anything else. He has never considered how to have iconic, snappy dialogue with an opponent.

“It’s enough.”, he responds, an answer that doesn’t really make sense grammatically. Enough height, presumably.

Of course, all of this is speculation. Everything but their words is separate from the physical reality of what is happening. I’m merely attempting a different style of prose, that incorporates these unknowable subtleties, at least slightly. (Apparently, having a sense of decorum and respect for the limits of narration and privacy amounts to ‘understanding people too much’, or something of the sort.) Please let me know if this is acceptable.

The black knight moves to withdraw his blade, as the only physical weapon he has on hand. But the white knight is experienced. Though no doctor, he knows that much of the potentially lethal bleeding from a wound only comes when the inserted object is *removed*. His brute, dumb, brilliance leads him to decide to just leave the thing in there until it falls out on its own. His opponent does not expect any of this. He expects the blow to cause a far longer period of recovery and stunlock. The irony is that if the white knight received his dreamed acclaim, this abnormal resilience would have been common knowledge among those aware they might have to fight him eventually.

He slams both fists down onto the skull of his vertically challenged foe, crumpling the young man’s composure and leaving him seeing stars with no blade in hand. The white knight uses this opportunity to draw his weapon. Thanks to magic, which, for note, has never stopped being a thing that exists, this ostentatious battleaxe is able to be far larger than anything that could reasonably be holstered.
The black knight jumps back, regaining his bearings. White pursues with a powerful swing. He misses.
Black launches an eldritch blast. White tanks the damage and slams his axe down, barely grazing his opponent. He grunts in annoyance. Black smirks, finally acclimated to the rhythm of this encounter.
Black uses evasive magic to make himself even harder to hit. White doesn’t seem to get the message. A part of him might even be enjoying this challenge. He uses the axe again. He misses.

Black launches another blast. White scowls.
“You can’t keep this up forever!”
“I won’t need to.” Black points out the obvious.

White has started bleeding significantly from that wound. The blade really isn’t guaranteed to save his life, and it inhibits his flexibility. Screaming, he tears it out quite roughly. The black knight grimaces at this beast going berserk.
White is also grimacing in pain. That was quite a nasty weapon. Serrated.  Highly damaging.
“Don’t fuck with me! Fight me like a man!”, the hemologically challenged white piece cries.

“I’m fighting you. I have no intention of fleeing.” His opponent calmly responds. He throws his cloak to the side, perhaps having become uncomfortably sweaty from the physical exercise. It gets caught on a nearby tree’s branch.
“You know damn well what I mean! Stop… stop fighting like a pussy!” White is furious. A sore loser, perhaps? He misses another blow, and endures another projectile.

The truth is that both sides are doing everything they can to win. White simply believes the manifestation of this principle for black is objectionable. How can he act like any sort of standards are reasonable in a fight to the death? Such irrationality is more common than one might think. With “one” being “some hypothetical observer completely foreign to all human cultures to have ever existed”. Perhaps that renders the figure of speech unhelpful.

White allows himself to receive easy answers in various metrics by classifying himself as “a man”. It explains what to prioritize and resolves him of any guilt for discrimination or his own sex drive or the agony dealt to all life advanced enough for self-awareness. Through this, he needs to approach things in the most direct and courageous way possible, constructing excuses for it not being his choice whenever he doesn’t do this.

If I were to attempt to be poetic, perhaps our “hero” truly is vital to this confrontation. Horatius, by their very nature, taught the lesson to the black knight that gender is not so cleanly defined, and it is not an unshakable objective maxim one must treat as gospel. This allows the taunts to not faze him in the slightest.

It could easily have been Jorge, though, really.

One thing that can be learned is from the one limit Black does enforce onto himself: he is not fleeing. Were it some random very strong guard, perhaps he would have attempted to avoid confrontation, and to seek other options. But this is different. He knows, vaguely, who this man is. What he represents.

The privileged fool, so he thinks, is blind to consequences. To what he’s up against, what he stands to lose. He’s dug his own grave by making the wound worse than it ever would’ve been by black’s efforts alone. And for what? A slightly faster swing? Black has given himself plenty of margin for error. A more accurate attack from white will still be an attack that misses. A part of black swells with pride. At last, his team will have bested one member of this alphabetically ordered family. Maybe that larger-than-life icon of a man would have finally been proud enough of him. He watches as the lumbering idiot approaches, and steps to the side like normal.
And as the sound of the axe dropping to the ground echoes, he feels two hands around his throat.

White shines the most the moment right after people conclude he’s an idiot. He is, to be clear; that’s what makes the deception so potent. But he can get the message after the same outcome happens three times. Even the penultimate swing was performed to encourage his presentation as a stubborn one-trick pony.

The waiting game has changed, and it’s clear black has much less time left. But as white squeezes harder and harder, he can’t help but notice that black doesn’t seem to be suffocating at all anymore. He’s just staring at the person currently preventing him from breathing. Though white would never figure out what exactly happened, his foe had repurposed magic intended for navigating underwater to circumvent the need to breathe. Such a thing takes focus and energy, but it certainly beats suffocating.

White realized the choking wasn’t working, and tried a different approach, hurling the man with incredible enhanced force right into the large specially-constructed covered carriage he came out of.

This turns out to be surprisingly effective. The wooden skeleton of the vehicle crumpled from the impact, leaving jagged rods and splinters all around. One of them rests comfortably within black’s abdomen, leaving him pinned. (This is the closest anyone in this fight gets to two others by proximity.)
White laughs. This is it. All his foe had going for him was movement. And that’s gone now.
In a world without healing magic, even if he survived, black would probably get tetanus, and have to deal with that whole ordeal. I just found that interesting.

Things are no longer happening at blistering speeds. White takes a moment to first fashion a compress for his wound, ripping his shirt to do so. 

While he does this, black starts exerting more energy. He levitates some of the cloth and bits of wood off his body. But the actual debilitating wound is left alone.

White notices and chuckles. “Don’t you know when you’re beat, kid?” He scratches his head. “I guess I respect it. To the bitter end. You know, I would’ve done the same! Just saying.” He feels the need to clarify this.

Black doesn’t respond. He’s only really social on a good day. He keeps lifting up bits of the carriage, even snapping some of them further in the process. Let no one say he never studied up on magic to manipulate physical matter.
“The chick you had flee… your mother, huh? If it helps you rest in peace, know that I’ll make sure the law treats her fairly. I’m a gentleman.”

Black gives a pained grunt. It’s unclear if this is a response to the enemy’s words or just to the effort exerted in his Sisyphean endeavor. At this point, with only a few bits of material left on the ground, he’s stopped lifting anything off himself.
He’s just putting his all into keeping those pieces of wood in the air, splitting them into even more fragments as he seemingly fumbles the amount of energy he’s using on each of them.

White looks upon this with pity, grabbing his axe from the ground with one hand and slowly approaching. It’s disconcerting to him that this boy looks determined to make sure his last moments are spent in desperate agony. It would seem even his loud machismo has a limit.

He gets close enough to see black’s face, and is slightly puzzled. He’s not paying attention to what he’s lifting at all. Nor is he looking at the encroaching foe, or just unable to look directly at anything in his pained state. His gaze is focused strongly at a specific point in the distance… at his opponent’s discarded cloak, caught on a tree and waving in the wind. Waving… increasingly faster…
White realizes something, and loses his composure as he screams a brief yelp of rage and hatred. But he doesn’t move quickly enough.

Jorge was a healer and took a support role. Bernard Zie analyzed and perfected magic of the earth and flora. He basically thinks it’s his whole personality. And Horatius Kyodu, when forced into self-defense, was partial to pelting foes with fire. But the black knight, Wress Hifele, never really specialized in anything elemental. After mastering the fundamentals that could make life more convenient, he made use of the physical world around him, moved objects and sounds and waves as he pleased until his limits were quite large indeed. All while trying to keep himself unassuming, and hold his cards close to his chest, so to speak.
He was always a bit of a coward. A street urchin. He learned to do a lot with only a little. To play dead and then bite ankles. It brings success at the cost of an inferiority complex.

And this was the reason for that scream. The white knight was not merely upset that he’d been outwitted. Sure: our white knight, Frank Praxis, hated losing. But more than that, this trick specifically relied on him underestimating the competition, pitying his sorry state and giving him time for plotting tricks. ‘That’s the last time I ever leave myself vulnerable!’, he thinks. And he’s right.

Apologies for jumping the gun, but this really shouldn’t be a surprise. As the ordering of events has been presented, this was a foregone conclusion. The next morning, MBMJ wakes up to see a city and government in full on panic mode. Solnit alludes to some event, but is not specific. The phrasing “we can’t let anyone else die today” imply this has to do with a significant death, likely also within the Praxis family, and the confrontation between Wress and Frank was only ever going to end with lethal force. If someone was prevented from reaching this conclusion because they didn’t know the man who stopped the group was Frank, well, that’s quite fitting, is it not?
Where exactly are the kings? Why are these two less vital pieces duking it out alone as if there was nothing more important to ever exist?
In chess, it is impossible for a king to ever die. In a situation where this would be about to happen, the world instead remains in stasis for all time.

But real life is not the same as chess. There’s far more filler. Though the scope necessarily means real life has more value, chess is certainly much denser in moments of intrigue when accounting for the amount of time and energy it takes. 

Even after Tebar Hifele is long gone, everything he left behind has to resolve itself.

There is one commonality, though. Chess doesn’t have battles. There wouldn’t really be a lengthy one to one encounter between two individual pieces as I’ve presented thus far. The capturer and the captured is determined entirely by the order of action and starting positions.

White is downwind. Black concentrates all the momentum of the air within a full kilometer of their location right to his vicinity. In exchange, he releases his concentration on all the debris he’s suspended in the air, allowing it to go where the wind takes it. Death by a thousand cuts. As was the plan, at least. Was it an act of desperation? Perhaps he thought that would be enough, or that he could set up a loop to repeat this indefinitely. I can’t say for certain if he would’ve been right about that. In reality, nothing of the sort was needed. White had lifted his weapon very casually and thoughtlessly under his assumption the fight was over. The blade was facing his neck. That’s all it took.
